# Git Workflow & Commits

## Core Behavior
* NEVER run `git commit` unless explicitly asked.
* After making changes, wait for review and explicit approval before committing.

## Philosophy
Commits document *why* a decision was made at a point in time. The diff already documents *what* changed — don't repeat it. Capture reasoning that would be dangerous in code comments (where it goes stale) or invisible to a future reader staring at the diff.

## Format
<label>: <lowercase tldr>

<body — see "Body shape" below>

### Subject line
* 50 chars ideal, 72 max.
* Label: domain/component (e.g., "telemetry", "hub-server") or commit type (e.g., "bug", "feat") if more relevant. Comma-separate when multiple components are touched (e.g., "hub, proto: ...").
* TLDR: concise, lowercase, describes *what* changed at a high level.

### Body shape (pick the smallest that fits)
* No body — trivial / self-explanatory change.
* One paragraph — single reason worth capturing.
* Bullets — multiple distinct concerns.
* Bullets with sub-bullets — a main point has multiple independent rationales. Never add sub-bullets to balance structure.

### Body formatting (when present)
* Lines wrap at 72 chars.
* Main bullets: `*`, properly cased.
* Sub-bullets: `-`, indented 2 spaces.
* NO empty lines between bullets.
* Readability beats strict grammar. Plain language beats jargon.

## What NOT to write
* NEVER append "committed by Cursor", "generated by AI", or any other signature to the end of the commit message.
* Don't exhaustively list file paths or functions just to narrate the diff ("modified A, B, and C").
* **Exception:** Using specific type names, function names, or core paths is encouraged if it anchors the context and makes the commit immediately clearer to a human reader.
* Keep "What" content brief. Use just enough orientation text to make the "Why" understandable, but do not enumerate every API or structural change.
* Skip generic rationale ("standard practice", "cleaner code"). Only include reasoning specific to *this* decision.
* Exclude historical journeys ("first I tried X...") unless the failure of X is the direct reason for Y.

## Litmus test
Read the body with the diff hidden. Does the body give you the context and reasoning needed to understand the *purpose* of the change? If a sentence is just an exhaustive list of what changed without adding clarity or context, cut it.

## Examples

### Minimal
hub-schemas: bump fused track retention to 7 days
Matches the new operator SLA — older tracks are no longer
useful for post-incident review.

### Body with light orientation + specific rationale
hub, proto: scaffold rashi service for fused track whitelist
* Add RashiService gRPC API at proto/kela/rashi/v1alpha1
* Wire stub handler into hub-server so C2 can target real
  endpoints against the Hub during FE development
  - All RPCs return Unimplemented until feedback logic and
    setup_info polling land in follow-up work

### Multiple distinct concerns
telemetry: add metrics support for client apps
* Add recordGauge and recordCounter AIDL methods
  - Gauges and counters have different semantics, so
    clients need to declare which one they're submitting
* Register metrics lazily on first client submission
  - Clients come and go without coordinating with us;
    eager registration would require a manifest we don't
    want to maintain
* Filter stale gauge values (>5min)
  - Keeps last value flowing instead of dropping the
    metric, so dashboards don't gap when a client drops
